import Foundation

enum CountryOverviewDescriptionStore {
    private static let customDescriptions: [String: String] = [
        "AD": "Andorra is a tiny Pyrenean principality wedged between France and Spain, and for centuries it survived by leaning into mountain autonomy rather than imperial scale. It is best known now for skiing, hiking, and duty-free shopping, but its older identity is tied to medieval charters and high valleys that were difficult to control from outside. The result is a country that feels improbably compact yet historically durable.",
        "AE": "The United Arab Emirates is a federation of seven emirates on the Arabian Gulf, built from old pearling and trading ports into one of the most engineered landscapes in the region. Dubai and Abu Dhabi dominate the global image, but the federation also includes mountain wadis, desert interiors, mangroves, and smaller emirates with very different rhythms. It is a modern state whose story only makes sense if you put glass towers beside Bedouin, maritime, and oil-era history.",
        "AF": "Afghanistan sits at the meeting point of Central and South Asia, and for centuries its mountain passes linked Persia, India, and the wider Silk Road world. It has deep traditions of poetry, carpet weaving, miniature painting, and regional cuisines shaped by valleys, orchards, and highland trade routes. The country carries a remarkably old and intricate cultural identity, with strong regional character from city bazaars to mountain valleys.",
        "AG": "Antigua and Barbuda is a two-island Caribbean state best known for calm turquoise water, sailing culture, and the claim that it has a beach for every day of the year. Antigua carries most of the population and much of the historic architecture, while Barbuda is flatter, wilder, and more lightly developed, with pink-sand beaches and major bird habitats. The country feels especially maritime, with harbors, reefs, and cricket all woven into its identity.",
        "AI": "Anguilla is a British Overseas Territory in the northeastern Caribbean known for beaches so calm and bright that the island often appears in luxury travel shorthand. What makes it more distinctive, though, is its small scale and lack of a giant cruise-port machine, which gives it a quieter, lower-density atmosphere than many resort islands. It is the kind of place where the geography stays intimate and the sea remains the main event.",
        "AL": "Albania is a western Balkan country on the Adriatic and Ionian Seas, shaped by Illyrian roots, long Ottoman rule, and decades of hard communist isolation under Enver Hoxha. That unusual twentieth-century history left behind bunker-studded landscapes, UNESCO towns like Berat and Gjirokaster, and a society that reopened to the wider world only in the 1990s. It also manages to fit alpine valleys, archaeological sites, and a striking Riviera coastline into a relatively small map.",
        "AM": "Armenia is a mountainous South Caucasus republic whose identity is closely tied to being one of the world's earliest Christian states. Its landscape is marked by monasteries, volcanic highlands, apricot orchards, and a stone-built architectural tradition that feels unmistakably Armenian. Even first-time visitors quickly notice how strongly music, food, craftsmanship, and memory are woven into daily life.",
        "AO": "Angola stretches from the Atlantic coast into high plateaus and interior river systems, giving it far more environmental range than many outsiders expect. It is also a country of strong musical identity, especially through semba and kizomba, and of regional cultures shaped by trade, migration, and Portuguese influence. Angola is still less visited than many African neighbors, which means its scale and cultural richness remain underappreciated internationally.",
        "AQ": "Antarctica is the only continent without an indigenous human population or ordinary cities, and that alone makes it unlike any other place represented in the app. Nearly everything here is organized around ice, scientific research, and the logistics of surviving extreme cold and isolation. People visit mainly by expedition ship, and the experience is less about sightseeing in the usual sense than about encountering planetary scale.",
        "AR": "Argentina stretches from subtropical forests to Patagonian ice fields, so its national map contains one of the widest climatic ranges on earth. It also produced one of Latin America's strongest urban cultures through Buenos Aires, with deep traditions in literature, psychoanalysis, football, and tango. The country is easiest to understand as a place where continental landscape and highly self-aware culture developed side by side.",
        "AS": "American Samoa is a US territory in Polynesia where village life, Christian tradition, and Samoan custom remain far more central than any resort image. Its steep volcanic islands and protected bays give it a dramatic Pacific geography, while its political status links it to the United States without making it culturally American in the usual sense. It is a territory where land, family, and chiefly structures still visibly matter.",
        "AT": "Austria sits in the center of Europe but is historically the remnant of a much larger Habsburg world that once stretched across the continent. Vienna still carries that imperial inheritance through music, museums, and urban design, while the rest of the country opens into alpine valleys, lake regions, and baroque towns. It is a place where state order, mountain scenery, and old dynastic prestige still overlap.",
        "AU": "Australia is both a continent and a modern nation-state, which is one reason its geography feels so outsized compared with its population. Long before British colonization it was home to hundreds of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander cultures, and that deeper history is essential to understanding the country. Today it combines coastal megacities with deserts, reefs, rainforests, and interior distances that shape almost every idea people have about it.",
        "AW": "Aruba sits just off the coast of Venezuela and is one of the Caribbean's driest islands, which is why its landscape leans toward cacti and wind-shaped scrub rather than dense rainforest. Its Dutch political status, Papiamento language, and South American proximity give it a cultural blend that does not read like a generic tropical island. The island is small, but it carries a surprisingly specific identity.",
        "AX": "The Aland Islands are a Swedish-speaking autonomous archipelago of Finland in the Baltic Sea, positioned between mainland Finland and Sweden. Their demilitarized status is one of their most distinctive features and has shaped local identity for more than a century. Ferries, red-granite shores, and maritime life make the islands feel more like a self-contained Baltic world than a peripheral afterthought.",
        "AZ": "Azerbaijan sits at the crossroads of the Caucasus and the Caspian, where Turkic, Persian, Russian, and Caucasian influences have long overlapped. Baku is famous for its oil wealth and flame-shaped skyline, but the country also includes mountain villages, Silk Road traces, and one of the world's oldest associations with petroleum. It is often described as a bridge between regions because its politics and culture genuinely sit in between several worlds.",
        "BA": "Bosnia and Herzegovina is a Balkan state where Ottoman, Austro-Hungarian, and Yugoslav layers remain visible in architecture, religion, and everyday speech. Sarajevo's cafe culture, Mostar's stone bridge, mountain landscapes, and deeply rooted coffee traditions make the country feel warm, layered, and unusually memorable. Few places explain the complexity of southeastern Europe more clearly once you start reading the landscape closely.",
        "BB": "Barbados is an eastern Caribbean island known for polished beaches, cricket culture, rum, and a confident national style that feels both elegant and easygoing. It became a republic only in 2021, which is surprisingly recent for a country so well known globally. The island is compact, sociable, and very good at turning seaside life into part of its identity.",
        "BD": "Bangladesh sits on the vast delta formed by the Ganges, Brahmaputra, and Meghna rivers, which makes water central to both its beauty and its daily life. It is a country of boat-filled river scenes, Bengali literary culture, rich textile traditions, and one of the most language-conscious national identities in the world. Densely populated and culturally confident, it is shaped as much by poetry, food, and music as by geography.",
        "BE": "Belgium is small in area but unusually dense in medieval cities, modern institutions, and regional identities divided mainly between Dutch-speaking Flanders and French-speaking Wallonia. Brussels functions both as a Belgian capital and as one of Europe's main political centers through the EU and NATO. It is a country people often underestimate until they notice how much art, politics, brewing, and linguistic complexity are packed into it.",
        "BF": "Burkina Faso is a landlocked West African country whose modern name means 'Land of Upright People,' replacing a colonial-era label after independence. It lies in the Sahel and has long been shaped by overland trade, Mossi state traditions, and the environmental pressures of dry-zone agriculture. Even when outsiders know little about it, the country has a strong political and cultural history within the region.",
        "BG": "Bulgaria sits between the Balkans, the Black Sea, and the old routes connecting Europe with Anatolia and the eastern Mediterranean. Its history includes Thracian antiquity, medieval Bulgarian empires, centuries under Ottoman rule, and a twentieth-century socialist period. That layered past helps explain why monasteries, Roman ruins, rose valleys, beach towns, and Soviet-era monuments can all belong to the same trip.",
        "BH": "Bahrain is a small island kingdom in the Gulf that built importance far beyond its size through pearling, trade, and later finance and oil. Its causeways, skyline, and Formula One profile make it appear hyper-modern, but older Bahrain was one of the region's key maritime societies. The country is easiest to understand as an island trading node that adapted early to the post-pearling Gulf economy.",
        "BI": "Burundi is a densely populated country in the African Great Lakes region, where hills, agriculture, and long social memory shape daily life. It shares historical and cultural ties with Rwanda while following its own distinct political path after independence. Because it rarely dominates international travel narratives, many people miss how old and regionally rooted its state traditions are.",
        "BJ": "Benin occupies a central place in the history of the Bight of Benin, especially through the Kingdom of Dahomey and the royal traditions that still shape its historical identity. It is also one of the principal homelands of Vodun, a religion often misunderstood abroad but deeply important in regional culture. The country's coastline is only part of the story; inland palaces, ceremonial heritage, and historical memory matter just as much.",
        "BL": "Saint Barthelemy is a French Caribbean collectivity known internationally for yachts and high-end tourism, but its small scale and unusual status make it more politically interesting than its image suggests. It was once Swedish before returning to French control in the nineteenth century, a fact many people never learn because the island now reads so strongly as French Caribbean. Today it functions as a tiny, wealthy outpost with a very specific social tone.",
        "BM": "Bermuda is a British Overseas Territory in the North Atlantic, far from the Caribbean despite often being grouped with it in tourism shorthand. It became globally famous not just for pastel houses and reefs, but for shipping lore, insurance, and offshore finance. The island's identity mixes old maritime history with a modern economy that is much more international than its size suggests.",
        "BN": "Brunei is a small, oil-rich sultanate on Borneo whose political structure remains centered on monarchy in a way that feels unusual in the contemporary world. It became wealthy through hydrocarbons, but its deeper identity is tied to Malay Islamic monarchy and a long riverine history. Because it is tucked between larger neighbors, many people know almost nothing about it until they notice how singular its state model is.",
        "BO": "Bolivia is one of South America's highest and most geographically dramatic countries, containing Andean highlands, Amazon lowlands, and the immense salt flats of Uyuni. It has one of the continent's largest Indigenous majorities, which gives questions of language, memory, and state identity unusual visibility in public life. The country often surprises people because its political and cultural center is not coastal but high, inland, and deeply Andean.",
        "BQ": "Bonaire, Sint Eustatius, and Saba are Caribbean special municipalities of the Netherlands, a constitutional arrangement that is more unusual than the islands' beach imagery suggests. Each island has a different personality, from Bonaire's diving culture to Saba's volcanic steepness and Sint Eustatius's historical role in Atlantic trade. Together they show how Dutch Caribbean geography does not fit neatly into one formula.",
        "BR": "Brazil is South America's largest country by both area and population, and its scale alone makes almost every summary incomplete. Portuguese colonization, Indigenous societies, and later immigration produced one of the world's most complex cultural blends, visible in everything from language and architecture to music and food. From the Amazon to Sao Paulo to Bahia, Brazil is better understood as a federation of strong regional worlds than as a single simple national mood.",
        "BS": "The Bahamas is an Atlantic archipelago of hundreds of islands and cays spread across shallow banks of intensely clear water. It became historically important through shipping routes, piracy lore, and later offshore finance and tourism rather than through one large landmass. Even though its image is leisure-heavy, the country's geography has always made it a crossroads state.",
        "BT": "Bhutan is a Himalayan kingdom that became internationally famous for measuring development through Gross National Happiness, though that idea is only one part of its identity. It remained relatively isolated for much of the twentieth century, which helped preserve strong Buddhist institutions and a visible architectural style. The country often fascinates people because it presents modernization as something to manage cautiously rather than worship automatically.",
        "BV": "Bouvet Island is one of the most remote islands on earth, a Norwegian dependency in the South Atlantic that is almost entirely glaciated and ringed by steep cliffs. It has no permanent residents, no normal visitor infrastructure, and almost no access except through rare expedition or research voyages. More than a destination in the usual sense, it is the kind of place people remember because it seems almost impossible that land can be this isolated.",
        "BW": "Botswana is a southern African republic whose international reputation is closely tied to conservation, stable governance, and the Okavango Delta. That delta is one of the world's great inland wetland systems, turning a dry interior landscape into a seasonal ecological spectacle. The country is often cited as a post-independence success story, but its environmental geography is just as defining as its politics.",
        "BY": "Belarus sits on the broad plains between Russia, Ukraine, Poland, and the Baltic world, a position that gave it a mixed East European identity shaped by forests, rivers, and borderland culture. Minsk is notably spacious and orderly, while the countryside is known for lakes, birch woods, village traditions, and a strong attachment to seasonal life. It is a country people often hear about politically before they ever notice its quieter, greener character.",
        "BZ": "Belize is the only mainland Central American country with English as its official language, a legacy of British colonial rule that immediately sets it apart from its neighbors. It also contains the Belize Barrier Reef, one of the great marine systems of the western hemisphere, alongside Maya archaeological sites and rainforest interiors. The country is small, but it sits at an unusually rich cultural and ecological junction.",
        "CA": "Canada is one of the world's largest countries, spanning the Atlantic, Pacific, and Arctic, yet most of its population lives relatively close to the US border. Its political identity is shaped by bilingual federalism, Indigenous nations, and the balancing act between enormous space and a comparatively modest population. It is a country where wilderness mythology and highly urban daily life coexist without cancelling each other out.",
        "CC": "The Cocos (Keeling) Islands are an Australian territory in the Indian Ocean whose small population and remoteness make them feel more like a maritime outpost than a conventional holiday island. They are especially distinctive for their long Malay cultural presence, which gives the territory a social history different from that of most Australian-administered places. The islands are tiny, but their identity is not generic at all.",
        "CD": "The Democratic Republic of the Congo is one of Africa's most resource-rich and geographically immense states, centered on the Congo River basin. It is also one of the continent's great cultural powerhouses, especially in music, dance, fashion, and urban creativity from Kinshasa outward. Any serious description has to hold both truths at once: extraordinary ecological and cultural richness, and a history of exploitation that has often obscured it.",
        "CF": "The Central African Republic sits near the geographic center of the continent, but despite that name it has often been politically and logistically peripheral. Forest, savanna, and river systems meet here, and the country's history is deeply tied to colonial extraction and later chronic instability. It is a place many people could not locate on a map, yet its story says a great deal about the costs of neglect and weak infrastructure.",
        "CG": "The Republic of the Congo lies west of the Congo River and is often overshadowed by its much larger neighbor across the water, though the two capitals facing each other is one of the world's great geographic oddities. It has Atlantic coastline, equatorial forest, colorful urban music culture, and a Francophone identity that feels distinct within Central Africa. The country rewards closer attention because people often know its name without knowing what actually makes it unique.",
        "CH": "Switzerland is famous for neutrality, banking, and alpine scenery, but it is also a multilingual federal state held together by a carefully cultivated civic compact. German, French, Italian, and Romansh all belong to the national story, which is one reason regional differences remain so visible. The country often feels efficient to visitors because the political system was built to manage diversity through local autonomy and painstaking coordination.",
        "CI": "Ivory Coast, or Cote d'Ivoire, became one of Francophone West Africa's major economic centers through cocoa, ports, and the growth of Abidjan into one of the region's most energetic cities. The country is also known for strong visual art, lively music scenes, and a mix of coastal and inland cultures that make it feel much bigger than a single export story. Agriculture matters, but so do fashion, nightlife, and the creative confidence of urban Ivory Coast.",
        "CK": "The Cook Islands are a self-governing state in free association with New Zealand, a constitutional relationship that is more nuanced than many people expect. Spread across a wide swath of the South Pacific, they combine Polynesian cultural continuity with administrative links to a larger power. Their remoteness is real, but so is their long tradition of navigation and ocean knowledge.",
        "CL": "Chile runs like a narrow ribbon down South America's Pacific edge, which is why it contains desert, Mediterranean valleys, fjords, glaciers, and subantarctic weather in one elongated strip. It was shaped by Spanish rule, Indigenous resistance, nineteenth-century state-building, and the global legacy of the Pinochet dictatorship. Geography gives Chile its visual drama, but political memory gives it a very different kind of depth.",
        "CM": "Cameroon is often called 'Africa in miniature' because it contains rainforest, coast, savanna, and highlands within one national map. It also sits at the meeting point of Francophone and Anglophone colonial legacies, a division that still shapes politics today. The country is unusually diverse in both language and landscape, which is why quick summaries almost always miss something important.",
        "CN": "China is one of the world's oldest continuous civilizations and one of its most consequential modern states, a combination that makes every simple description feel inadequate. Imperial capitals, socialist history, manufacturing power, religious landscapes, mountain frontiers, and megacities all belong to the same national frame. To understand China at all, you have to accept both its immense internal diversity and its long continuity.",
        "CO": "Colombia is one of the few South American countries with both Caribbean and Pacific coastlines, and that dual maritime geography helps explain its cultural range. It includes Andean cities, coffee landscapes, Amazonian zones, Afro-Caribbean coast, and one of the most rhythmically rich music cultures in the region, from cumbia to vallenato. The country feels especially rewarding because each region speaks with such a different accent, flavor, and pace.",
        "CR": "Costa Rica became internationally famous for national parks and biodiversity, but its political history matters too: it abolished its army in 1948 and invested heavily in civil institutions instead. That decision helped shape the country's stable reputation within Central America. The country is small, yet it punches far above its weight in environmental imagination.",
        "CU": "Cuba is the Caribbean's largest island and one of the few places in the region whose global identity is inseparable from revolution and geopolitics. Spanish colonialism, the sugar economy, the 1959 revolution, and decades of US sanctions all helped shape the modern state. Music, architecture, medicine, migration, and ideology all sit unusually close together in the Cuban story.",
        "CV": "Cabo Verde is an Atlantic island nation off West Africa whose dry volcanic landscapes and maritime history produced a culture oriented as much toward music and migration as toward land. The islands are especially famous for morna and coladeira, and they often feel more airy, musical, and sea-facing than tropical in the classic lush-island sense. Many people know the sound before they know the map, which is actually a fitting way into the country.",
        "CW": "Curacao is a Dutch Caribbean island just off Venezuela whose brightly colored waterfront has become iconic, but its history is far more than a postcard. It developed a notably plural society shaped by Dutch, African, Sephardic Jewish, and Latin American influences, which gives the island a cultural life much richer than its size suggests. The island's character comes from that layered Atlantic history as much as from the beaches.",
        "CX": "Christmas Island is an Australian territory in the Indian Ocean best known scientifically and visually for its enormous red crab migration. Its population history is also unusual, with strong Chinese and Malay influences that make the island feel culturally unlike mainland Australia. It is a place where ecology and remoteness dominate the imagination almost immediately.",
        "CY": "Cyprus sits in the eastern Mediterranean at a crossroads of Greek, Turkish, Levantine, and wider imperial histories. Since 1974 the island has been divided, and that political reality shapes everything from border crossings to memory. Archaeology, beaches, monasteries, and modern geopolitics all exist here at once, which makes Cyprus far more than a generic resort island.",
        "CZ": "Czechia grew out of the historic lands of Bohemia and Moravia and carries one of Central Europe's strongest urban and architectural inheritances. Prague is world famous, but the country is also shaped by industrial history, spa towns, beer culture, and the long shadow of both Habsburg and communist rule. It often surprises visitors by being more intellectually and regionally varied than the fairytale image suggests.",
        "DE": "Germany sits at the center of Europe and brings together industrial precision, strong regional identity, forest landscapes, beer traditions, and cities with sharply different personalities. Hamburg, Bavaria, Berlin, the Rhine, and the Black Forest can feel like different countries in temperament, which is part of what makes traveling across Germany so interesting. It is a place where efficiency, festivals, museums, and everyday comfort all coexist easily.",
        "DJ": "Djibouti occupies a tiny but strategically immense position at the mouth of the Red Sea, opposite the Arabian Peninsula. Beyond that map significance, it is visually one of the most striking places in the Horn of Africa, with salt lakes, volcanic terrain, whale sharks, and desert landscapes that look almost extraterrestrial. The country feels less like a conventional sightseeing stop and more like a place of raw geological spectacle.",
        "DK": "Denmark is a maritime kingdom of islands and peninsulas whose history was shaped by seafaring, trade, and a very old monarchy. Modern Denmark is associated with design, cycling, and welfare-state efficiency, but it also has a deeper story rooted in the Baltic and North Sea worlds. Even its compactness feels deliberate, as if the country was designed to make everyday life workable.",
        "DM": "Dominica is often called the 'Nature Isle' of the Caribbean because it is mountainous, heavily forested, and much less built out than many neighboring islands. It also has one of the region's most visible surviving Indigenous communities, the Kalinago Territory. The island's identity comes less from resort polish than from volcanic terrain, rainfall, and resilience after storms.",
        "DO": "The Dominican Republic shares Hispaniola with Haiti but developed along a distinct Spanish colonial path that still shapes language, architecture, and state identity. It was the site of the first permanent European settlement in the Americas after 1492, which gives the country an outsized place in colonial history. Today it is known for beaches and music, but its longer historical significance is easy to miss if you only read the resort map.",
        "DZ": "Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, with Mediterranean cities in the north and the vast Sahara covering most of its territory. It is a country of enormous scale where Arab, Amazigh, Mediterranean, and Saharan histories all matter at once, from Casbah streets to desert oases and Roman ruins. The range is so large that Algeria often feels like several different worlds under one flag.",
        "EC": "Ecuador takes its name from the equator, and its compact territory manages to include Pacific coast, Andes, Amazon, and the Galapagos. That compressed geography is one reason the country feels so varied despite its modest size. It is also shaped by strong Indigenous presence and highland-lowland contrasts that run through politics, cuisine, and daily life.",
        "EE": "Estonia is a Baltic republic whose language is closer to Finnish than to the Indo-European languages around it, which already hints at how distinctive it is. It is often cited as a technology success story, but the older layers of Hanseatic town life, sauna culture, forests, islands, and northern design sensibility are just as important. The country feels especially appealing if you like places that are both digitally modern and quietly nature-bound.",
        "EG": "Egypt is one of the world's foundational civilizations, organized historically around the Nile's narrow fertility in the middle of desert landscapes. Ancient temples and pyramids are only one layer; the country is also Arab, Mediterranean, African, and deeply shaped by Islamic scholarship and modern state politics. Cairo alone makes clear that Egypt is not a museum piece but a living civilizational center.",
        "EH": "Western Sahara is a disputed territory on the Atlantic edge of North Africa whose political status remains unresolved decades after Spain withdrew. Much of it is controlled by Morocco, while the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic claims sovereignty and administers areas east of the berm. Any description has to start with that unresolved condition, because politics here is geography.",
        "ER": "Eritrea sits on the Red Sea coast of the Horn of Africa, where highland cities, port towns, and old trade routes shaped a culture that feels both East African and distinctly Red Sea. Asmara is one of the architectural surprises of the continent, with an extraordinary concentration of Italian modernist buildings, palm-lined boulevards, and cafe culture at high altitude. The country also carries strong traditions of coffee, music, and tightly knit community life that many outsiders never hear about.",
        "ES": "Spain is not just one culture but a state of strong historical regions, each with its own language traditions, cuisine, and political memory. Castilian, Catalan, Basque, Galician, Andalusian, and other identities all shape the map in visible ways. That is why Spain can hold Roman ruins, Islamic architecture, Atlantic fishing towns, and Mediterranean beach cities without ever feeling culturally flat.",
        "ET": "Ethiopia is one of Africa's most historically distinctive states, with an imperial tradition that was never colonized in the same way as most of the continent. Its script, church history, calendar, and food culture give it a civilizational profile that feels strongly its own. The country is easiest to understand not as a peripheral case but as one of the region's old historical centers.",
        "FI": "Finland lies between Scandinavia and Russia, and its identity blends northern calm with a very strong attachment to forests, lakes, sauna culture, and design. Helsinki feels clean-lined and understated, while the rest of the country opens into cabins, archipelagos, Lapland light, and a way of life that stays close to the seasons. The country's calm surface is part of the appeal rather than just a stereotype.",
        "FJ": "Fiji is a South Pacific island nation of volcanic islands, coral reefs, and strong village traditions anchored in Indigenous iTaukei culture. It also has a large Indo-Fijian community, a legacy of indentured labor under British rule that deeply shaped the country. Many people know the resort image first, but Fiji is more interesting when read as a multiethnic island state with its own political history.",
        "FK": "The Falkland Islands are a South Atlantic British Overseas Territory known for windswept grasslands, huge seabird colonies, and wildlife that often outnumbers people by an absurd margin. Penguins, albatrosses, and marine life dominate the landscape, which is why the islands are especially beloved by birders and expedition travelers. Their remoteness is real, but so is the quiet appeal of a place built around weather, sea, and open space.",
        "FM": "The Federated States of Micronesia is a sovereign Pacific state spread across a huge ocean area, which means the map is defined more by sea distance than by landmass. It is compact politically but geographically dispersed across island groups with distinct local histories. The country shows how a nation can be unified constitutionally while remaining profoundly archipelagic in lived reality.",
        "FO": "The Faroe Islands are a self-governing territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, set in the North Atlantic between Scotland, Iceland, and Norway. Steep green slopes, turf-roof traditions, and fishing-based livelihoods give the islands a very strong sense of place. They are often described as remote, but in historical terms they belong to a long seafaring North Atlantic world.",
        "FR": "France combines one of the world's most recognizable national cultures with deep internal regional differences that never fully disappear into the republic. It has been central to modern ideas about statehood, secularism, cuisine, fashion, literature, and political revolution for centuries. Yet much of its charm still comes from provincial variation, where Brittany, Provence, Corsica, Alsace, and the Basque Country each insist on their own story.",
        "GA": "Gabon sits on the equator in west-central Africa and is one of the continent's most forested states, with significant stretches of protected habitat. Oil wealth and low population density give it a very different profile from many neighboring countries. It is often overlooked, but it matters as both a conservation case and a former French colonial state with unusual ecological assets.",
        "GB": "The United Kingdom is a state made up of England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland, and understanding it requires keeping those internal nations in view. Empire, industrialization, monarchy, parliamentary tradition, and deindustrialization all shaped the modern country in ways that still remain visible. It is globally familiar, yet many outsiders still underestimate how regionally varied and historically layered it is.",
        "GD": "Grenada is a Caribbean island state known as the 'Spice Isle' because nutmeg, cinnamon, and other spices remain tied to its identity. Its green hills, crater lake, and compact harbor towns give it a more garden-like feel than many flatter Caribbean islands. The country is small enough to feel intimate, but distinctive enough that people tend to remember its scent and color as much as its beaches.",
        "GE": "Georgia sits in the Caucasus between Europe and Asia, though it often insists on its own civilizational frame rather than choosing either label. It claims one of the world's oldest wine traditions, and food, mountains, monasteries, and polyphonic music all play unusually strong roles in national self-understanding. The country feels distinct because its cultural confidence is older than many of the states around it.",
        "GF": "French Guiana is an overseas department of France on the north coast of South America, where Amazonian rainforest covers most of the territory and European political status creates an unusual combination. It is one of the few places in the world where a space center, Creole culture, riverside communities, and tropical forest all belong to the same map. The territory feels less like a classic Caribbean outpost and more like a deeply green frontier with a very unusual legal identity.",
        "GG": "Guernsey is a self-governing Crown Dependency in the English Channel, not part of the UK but closely tied to it. Its Norman roots, cliff paths, harbor towns, and old stone lanes give it a personality that feels both British and distinctly Channel Island. It is one of those places where constitutional nuance and coastal charm belong to the same identity.",
        "GH": "Ghana sits on the Gulf of Guinea and is often one of the easiest countries in West Africa for first-time visitors to fall in love with because the energy feels immediately warm, social, and self-assured. It brings together Akan heritage, Atlantic history, cocoa country, kente weaving, highlife music, and cities where fashion, art, and food culture are especially vibrant. Many people arrive expecting a history lesson and leave remembering the hospitality, color, and creative confidence of everyday life.",
        "GI": "Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory at the entrance to the Mediterranean, attached physically to the Iberian Peninsula but politically set apart from it. The Rock, the macaques, and the mix of British, Spanish, and Mediterranean influences give it a personality far larger than its size. It feels like a miniature crossroads where geography does most of the storytelling.",
        "GL": "Greenland is the world's largest island and an autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, though many Greenlanders see the future in terms of greater self-government or independence. Most of the landmass is covered by ice, which means settlement hugs the coasts in a pattern unusual for such a large place. It is central to Arctic politics, climate science, and Indigenous Inuit history all at once.",
        "GM": "The Gambia is a narrow West African state built around the Gambia River, which cuts inland almost like a corridor. Its unusual shape is a direct legacy of colonial boundary-making between British and French spheres. That geography makes the river not just a feature but the organizing logic of the whole country.",
        "GN": "Guinea is rich in bauxite and water resources, with the headwaters of major West African rivers rising in its highlands. It was also the only French colony in sub-Saharan Africa to vote for immediate independence in 1958, a choice with lasting symbolic significance. The country is often overlooked internationally despite having both political and environmental importance in the region.",
        "GP": "Guadeloupe is a French Caribbean archipelago whose butterfly-shaped main islands, volcanic slopes, markets, and Creole food culture give it a lively sense of place. Although it is politically part of France, daily life feels unmistakably Caribbean through language, music, rum, and the rhythm of island towns. It offers the unusual experience of tropical landscapes paired with French institutions, which makes the territory feel culturally layered rather than generic.",
        "GQ": "Equatorial Guinea is one of Africa's smallest countries, but its profile is unusually complex because it is the continent's only sovereign state with Spanish as an official language. Oil wealth transformed the economy, while island-and-mainland geography gives the country two quite different physical settings. It is a state whose language and political structure surprise many people the first time they look closely.",
        "GR": "Greece has an outsized presence in world imagination because classical antiquity is only one part of a much longer history that also includes Byzantium, Ottoman rule, and a modern nation-state. The country is split between a mountainous mainland and thousands of islands, which helps explain its intense local variation. It is not only ancient; it is also deeply maritime and regionally specific.",
        "GS": "South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands are a remote British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, known for glaciers, king penguins, and the legacy of polar exploration. South Georgia in particular is tied to the story of Ernest Shackleton, whose failed Antarctic expedition became legendary for survival rather than conquest. These islands are easier to imagine as wildlife and expedition country than as ordinary human territory.",
        "GT": "Guatemala was a major center of the Maya world, and that civilizational depth is still visible in archaeology, textiles, languages, and contemporary Indigenous life. Volcanic highlands, colonial cities, lake towns, and lowland jungles give the country remarkable visual contrast within a compact frame. It is one of the best places in the Americas to see ancient continuity still shaping clothing, markets, and daily ritual.",
        "GU": "Guam is an unincorporated US territory in the western Pacific where Chamoru culture, reef-lined shores, and tropical island life shape the place at least as much as its political status does. Family, food, fiestas, and village identity remain central to the island's character. Guam is often reduced to beaches and bases, but its Indigenous history and Pacific culture are just as central.",
        "GW": "Guinea-Bissau is a small West African state of mainland coast and island-studded estuaries, especially the Bijagos archipelago. It played an important role in anti-colonial struggle through the independence movement led by Amilcar Cabral. Many people know little about it, yet its political history is unusually significant in Lusophone Africa.",
        "GY": "Guyana sits on the northern coast of South America but is often culturally grouped with the Caribbean because of its language, colonial history, and migration patterns. It is one of the few countries on the continent with English as the official language, and it contains immense rainforest interior beyond its coastal settlements. In recent years, major offshore oil discoveries have begun to change how the world talks about it.",
        "HK": "Hong Kong is a Chinese special administrative region whose identity was shaped by British colonial rule, Cantonese culture, global finance, and one of the most intense urban skylines on earth. For decades it functioned as a distinctive bridge between China and the wider world. Any current description also has to recognize how dramatically politics and civil liberties have changed in recent years.",
        "HM": "Heard Island and McDonald Islands are an Australian external territory in the southern Indian Ocean, with no permanent residents and access so difficult that most people will never come remotely close to them. The territory is valued mainly for science, conservation, and the fact that it contains one of Australia's active volcanoes on Heard Island. It belongs more to the world of expedition logistics than to tourism.",
        "HN": "Honduras sits in the mountainous heart of Central America with both Caribbean and Pacific access, though most of its coastline identity is tied to the Caribbean side. It was home to Maya centers such as Copan and later became deeply entangled in the politics of US fruit companies, the origin of the phrase 'banana republic.' The country is more historically loaded than its quick summaries usually imply.",
        "HR": "Croatia combines Adriatic island chains, Roman heritage, Habsburg traces, and inland Balkan geography in one relatively compact state. Stone towns, ferry routes, seafood, vineyards, and clear coastal light give the country an atmosphere that is immediately easy to like. The result is a place where island hopping and old-world urban texture belong naturally together.",
        "HT": "Haiti shares the island of Hispaniola with the Dominican Republic and carries one of the Caribbean's most original cultural signatures, shaped through Creole language, Vodou traditions, painting, metalwork, music, and a fiercely expressive sense of identity. Port-au-Prince, Jacmel, mountain towns, and coastal communities all contribute different textures, from literary life and carnival to gingerbread architecture and artisan workshops. It is one of those places where artistic imagination is not a side note but one of the clearest ways to understand the country.",
        "HU": "Hungary sits in the Carpathian Basin and has long been shaped by its position between western, central, and southeastern Europe. Budapest's grand architecture reflects the Austro-Hungarian era, while thermal baths, plains, and wine regions point to other layers of the national story. It is a country where imperial memory and a very distinct language combine to make the identity feel unusually self-contained.",
        "ID": "Indonesia is the world's largest archipelagic state, stretching across thousands of islands between the Indian and Pacific Oceans. Java, Sumatra, Bali, Sulawesi, Borneo, and Papua each bring different historical and cultural worlds into the same republic. It is impossible to understand the country without thinking about scale, sea routes, Islam, colonialism, and regional diversity all together.",
        "IE": "Ireland's modern identity is inseparable from colonization, famine, migration, independence, and the enduring cultural power of language and literature. Although the island is small, its diaspora and political history gave it influence far beyond its size. Rural landscapes matter, but so do the memory and storytelling traditions that have shaped how Ireland presents itself to the world.",
        "IL": "Israel is a state established in 1948 on the eastern Mediterranean, and its modern identity is inseparable from a landscape that ranges from coastal cities and citrus country to desert expanses and the Dead Sea. Jerusalem, Tel Aviv, Haifa, and the Galilee each project very different rhythms, from religious pilgrimage and layered sacred history to beaches, nightlife, and technology-driven urban life. The country is geographically small, but it sits at the meeting point of Jewish history, regional cuisines, and some of the most symbolically charged cities in the world.",
        "IM": "The Isle of Man is a self-governing Crown Dependency in the Irish Sea with its own parliament, Tynwald, often described as one of the oldest continuous parliamentary bodies in the world. Norse, Celtic, and British influences all helped shape the island's identity. Today it is known as much for finance and the TT motorcycle races as for its constitutional peculiarities.",
        "IN": "India is one of the world's great civilizational centers, and its scale of language, religion, cuisine, and geography is so large that every generalization breaks down somewhere. The Himalayas, Indo-Gangetic plains, Deccan Plateau, tropical coasts, megacities, and temple towns all belong to the same national frame. It is not just diverse in a casual sense; it is dense with parallel histories happening at once.",
        "IO": "The British Indian Ocean Territory is a contested British-administered territory in the central Indian Ocean, most famously associated with Diego Garcia. Its modern history cannot be separated from the forced removal of the Chagossian people and the continuing sovereignty dispute involving Mauritius. This is one of those places where the most important fact is not scenery but political injustice.",
        "IR": "Iran is one of the world's old civilizational states, heir to Persian imperial traditions that long predate the modern republic. Its cultural influence runs through poetry, architecture, philosophy, carpets, cuisine, and urban life from Isfahan to Shiraz to Tehran. It is often framed abroad only through geopolitics, but that lens hides the depth and continuity that make the country so historically important.",
        "IS": "Iceland sits on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, which is why volcanic energy, geothermal heat, glaciers, and black-sand coasts all belong so naturally to the same place. It was settled by Norse voyagers and later developed one of Europe's best-preserved literary traditions through the sagas. The country often looks otherworldly, but it is equally interesting as a small society that learned to live with raw geology.",
        "IT": "Italy is a unified state built from regions that were for centuries separate republics, kingdoms, and duchies, which is why local identity still runs so deep. Rome, Florence, Venice, Naples, Sicily, and the Alps each pull the national story in different historical directions. Italy's cultural fame is real, but the deeper fascination is how much variety survived inside a single country.",
        "IQ": "Iraq sits at the heart of Mesopotamia, the land between the Tigris and Euphrates where some of the world's earliest cities, writing systems, and states first took shape. Beyond that ancient legacy, the country is also known for date palms, marshlands in the south, Abbasid-era Baghdad, poetry, hospitality, and rich regional food traditions. Its importance is civilizational as much as political, and the cultural depth stretches from ancient urban history to living culinary and literary traditions.",
        "JE": "Jersey is a Crown Dependency in the Channel Islands, closer to France than to most of England and still shaped by old Norman legal traditions that make it constitutionally unusual. It is not part of the United Kingdom, a distinction many people miss until they look at how its parliament, taxes, and self-government actually work. Beyond finance, the island is known for cliff walks, mild weather, dairy farming, and a small-scale coastal life that feels more Channel than British mainland.",
        "JM": "Jamaica is one of the Caribbean's most globally influential islands in music, language, athletics, and popular culture. British colonialism, Maroon resistance, Rastafari, and migration all shaped the modern nation, helping create a cultural voice that is instantly recognizable around the world. The island is physically small, but its cultural reach has been enormous.",
        "JO": "Jordan sits between the Levant and Arabia, and much of its modern significance comes from being a relatively stable state in a highly unstable neighborhood. Petra is world famous, but Roman ruins, desert castles, biblical associations, and the Dead Sea are all part of the country's historical range. Its geography is compact, yet it is constantly read through the larger politics of the region.",
        "JP": "Japan is an island country where state continuity, technological sophistication, and highly developed aesthetic traditions all coexist with unusual ease. Tea culture, seasonal food, shrine rituals, rail travel, neighborhood life, and an extraordinary eye for detail all shape the experience of being there. The country feels singular because it modernized dramatically without erasing older ritual and seasonal sensibilities.",
        "KE": "Kenya sits across the equator in East Africa and occupies a central place in the popular imagination of safari travel, though that is only one layer of the country. Swahili coast history, highland agriculture, modern urban culture in Nairobi, and long-distance running all belong just as much to the national identity. It is best understood as a place where wildlife, commerce, and contemporary creativity meet.",
        "KG": "Kyrgyzstan is one of Central Asia's most mountainous states, and its high pastures, yurts, and horse culture still shape how the country imagines itself. Much of its history was nomadic before Russian and Soviet incorporation changed the political frame. Even now it often feels defined less by cities than by routes through mountain space.",
        "KH": "Cambodia is inseparable from Angkor, one of the most impressive premodern temple complexes on earth, but the country is more than the ruins that made it famous. Buddhist continuity, river life along the Mekong and Tonle Sap, distinctive Khmer design, and a younger creative scene give modern Cambodia far more texture than a single monument can capture. It is one of those places where elegance, spirituality, and daily life still feel closely linked.",
        "KI": "Kiribati is a Pacific nation of low coral atolls spread across an enormous area of ocean, so its geography is more dispersed than many people can easily picture. It straddles the equator and, after a line adjustment, the International Date Line, which gives it a quirky place in discussions of time and global cartography. Sea-level rise is not abstract here; it is a direct national reality.",
        "KM": "Comoros is an island state in the Mozambique Channel whose culture reflects African, Arab, Persian, and French connections. The islands are volcanic, fragrant with ylang-ylang and cloves, and less internationally visible than nearby Indian Ocean destinations. Their history and language make clear that the western Indian Ocean was never a simple edge of Africa, but a connected maritime world.",
        "KN": "Saint Kitts and Nevis is the smallest sovereign state in the western hemisphere by both area and population. Despite that scale, it played an outsized role in colonial Caribbean history because Saint Kitts was one of Britain's earliest and most important sugar islands. Today the federation is small enough to feel intimate, but not small enough to be historically simple.",
        "KP": "North Korea occupies the northern half of the Korean Peninsula and is one of the world's most sealed-off societies, which is why outsiders usually know the state image before they know much about the country itself. Behind that image lies a landscape of mountains, cold winters, rice fields, and cities shaped by a highly centralized style of planning and public symbolism. Its Korean language, food traditions, seasonal customs, and everyday routines are far less visible internationally than its politics, which is part of what makes it so difficult to understand from afar.",
        "KR": "South Korea transformed in a few decades into one of the world's most technologically advanced and culturally influential countries. Confucian inheritance, industrial policy, democratization, K-pop, cinema, skincare, street food, and highly competitive urban life all play major roles in the modern national story. It is a country where rapid change happened fast enough that several eras still feel visible at once.",
        "KW": "Kuwait is a small Gulf monarchy whose modern wealth came from oil, but its earlier history was rooted in pearling, maritime trade, and desert-edge settlement. Seafront life, diwaniya culture, food, and a long memory of merchant society still shape the country's identity beneath the skyline. Kuwait is often overshadowed by larger neighbors, yet it has one of the Gulf's clearest small-state personalities.",
        "KY": "The Cayman Islands are a British Overseas Territory best known internationally for offshore finance, a role that gives them influence far beyond their physical size. They also sit in classic Caribbean turquoise waters, which can make the economy's abstract global significance easy to overlook. In practice the islands are both tropical and deeply embedded in international legal and financial systems.",
        "KZ": "Kazakhstan is the world's largest landlocked country, stretching across steppe, desert, mountain, and Caspian landscapes in enormous proportions. It was shaped by nomadic traditions, Russian imperial expansion, Soviet industrialization, and post-Soviet state-building under a highly managed political system. The scale is so large that the country often feels more Eurasian than neatly Central Asian.",
        "LA": "Laos is a landlocked Southeast Asian state organized historically around the Mekong, Buddhist culture, and older kingdoms such as Lan Xang. Monasteries, river towns, forested mountains, night markets, and a slower social tempo give the country a gentle atmosphere that many travelers remember vividly. It is a place whose appeal comes less from spectacle than from texture, calm, and the way daily life stays close to the landscape.",
        "LB": "Lebanon occupies a small strip of the eastern Mediterranean, but for millennia it has acted as a meeting place for trade, religion, and empire. Phoenician memory, mountain villages, cafe life, design culture, and one of the region's most celebrated cuisines all belong to the national story. The country's size is deceptive because its cultural and historical density is so high.",
        "LC": "Saint Lucia is a Caribbean island whose twin Pitons are among the region's most recognizable volcanic landmarks. French and British competition shaped its colonial past so intensely that control changed hands many times before independence. The island's beauty is obvious, but its linguistic and historical layering is just as interesting.",
        "LI": "Liechtenstein is a tiny Alpine principality between Switzerland and Austria, one of the world's few remaining states still centered on a ruling prince in a very visible way. It is wealthy, highly industrialized, and also known for finance, yet physically it is little more than a mountain valley and villages. Its scale makes it seem improbable, which is part of the fascination.",
        "LK": "Sri Lanka is an island off India's southern tip whose history runs through Buddhism, Tamil and Sinhalese cultures, Indian Ocean trade, and layered colonial eras. Because the island is relatively compact, it combines ancient cities, tea country, surf coast, wildlife reserves, and spice-rich cuisine within short distances. It rewards people who think of it as a civilizational island, not just a beach destination.",
        "LR": "Liberia was founded in the nineteenth century by settlers from the United States, a beginning that gives it one of the most unusual state origins in Africa. Its Atlantic coastline, English-language identity, local food culture, and layered social history make it feel unlike any neighboring country. Liberia is impossible to understand without that unusual founding story, but it is just as memorable for the distinct society that grew from it.",
        "LS": "Lesotho is a mountain kingdom entirely surrounded by South Africa, making it one of the world's very few enclaved sovereign states. Because much of the country lies at high elevation, it is sometimes called the 'Kingdom in the Sky.' Its geography shaped a strong sense of distinctness even while labor migration tied many Basotho lives to South Africa.",
        "LT": "Lithuania was once part of a vast medieval commonwealth with Poland, a fact that surprises people who assume it has always been a small Baltic state. Today it is known for baroque Vilnius, basketball, forests, lakes, folk song, and a Baltic identity that feels both historic and quietly modern. Its scale is small, but the cultural self-confidence is not.",
        "LU": "Luxembourg is one of Europe's smallest sovereign states, yet it became one of its wealthiest and most institutionally significant. It sits between France, Germany, and Belgium, and that borderland position shaped its multilingual character and strategic history. The country often looks understated, but it plays a remarkably oversized role in European finance and governance.",
        "LV": "Latvia sits on the eastern Baltic with a history shaped by trade, ports, forests, and long connections to wider northern Europe. Riga's architecture, choir traditions, midsummer celebrations, and nearby beaches give the country a cultural life that feels both urban and nature-oriented. The modern republic feels distinctly Baltic, with a strong sense of rhythm, design, and season.",
        "LY": "Libya spans Mediterranean coast, desert interior, and old caravan routes, but much of the country is now understood through the collapse of state authority after the fall of Muammar Gaddafi. Earlier layers include Greek and Roman cities, Ottoman rule, Italian colonization, and oil-led modern state formation. The map is vast, and so is the gap between its archaeological richness and its present instability.",
        "MA": "Morocco sits where the Atlantic, Mediterranean, Sahara, and Atlas Mountains meet, so its geography produces unusual range within one country. Arab, Amazigh, Andalusi, Jewish, and French influences all helped shape the kingdom's cities, cuisine, and language politics. It is one of North Africa's most legible travel destinations, but the deeper story is about layered identity rather than just visual beauty.",
        "MC": "Monaco is the second-smallest sovereign state in the world, built on a narrow strip of Mediterranean coast beside France. Its global image is tied to royalty, casinos, luxury real estate, and the Formula One Grand Prix, all compressed into barely more than a neighborhood's worth of land. Few places are so small yet so recognizable.",
        "MD": "Moldova is a largely rural country between Romania and Ukraine whose identity is often discussed through language, wine, and the unresolved status of Transnistria. It was long part of larger imperial systems and only became independent after the Soviet collapse. Because it sits between stronger regional poles, its own history is often underestimated.",
        "ME": "Montenegro is one of Europe's smallest states, but it compresses Adriatic coast, steep mountains, deep canyons, and a long tradition of fiercely defended autonomy. It spent much of modern history tied to Yugoslav frameworks before reestablishing full independence in 2006. The country is so compact that it can feel almost designed to demonstrate geographic contrast quickly.",
        "MF": "Saint Martin, on the French side of the island shared with Sint Maarten, is a French overseas collectivity with a Caribbean setting and European administrative ties. The island is famous for its divided sovereignty, an arrangement that is surprisingly old and relatively peaceful by world standards. Its identity is shaped as much by that border oddity as by beaches.",
        "MG": "Madagascar broke away from the African mainland tens of millions of years ago, which is why its biodiversity is so famously strange and rich. It was also a kingdom, later a French colony, and now a large island state where Asian, African, and local Malagasy influences meet. Many people know the lemurs; fewer know how distinctive the human history is as well.",
        "MH": "The Marshall Islands are low Pacific atolls spread across a huge area of ocean, and their modern history is inseparable from US nuclear testing in Bikini and Enewetak. That history left environmental, political, and medical legacies that still matter deeply. The country is beautiful, but any serious description has to acknowledge what was done there.",
        "MK": "North Macedonia occupies an inland Balkan crossroads where Slavic, Ottoman, Orthodox, Albanian, and Yugoslav histories all overlap. Lake Ohrid is one of Europe's oldest and deepest lakes, and it anchors one of the country's strongest historical landscapes. The modern state is young in name, but the region it covers has been culturally layered for a very long time.",
        "ML": "Mali has long stood at the heart of Sahelian and Saharan history through empires, caravan trade, Islamic scholarship, and music traditions with global influence. Timbuktu became a symbol of remoteness in foreign imagination, yet historically it was a center of knowledge and exchange. The country's current instability should not erase how central it has been to West African history.",
        "MM": "Myanmar bridges South and Southeast Asia, and its river plains, ethnic diversity, Buddhist monuments, and teak-and-gold architecture make it one of the region's most visually distinctive countries. Tea shops, temple plains, lacquerware, longyi, and regional cuisines give everyday life a strong cultural texture that visitors remember easily. Bagan's pagodas, Inle Lake's stilt villages, Mandalay's craft traditions, and Yangon tea culture all reveal a country with a very recognizable personality of its own.",
        "MN": "Mongolia is the classic land of steppe, sky, horses, and mobility, and it still carries the world-historical weight of the Mongol Empire. Outside Ulaanbaatar, much of the country remains sparsely populated in a way that makes scale feel immediate rather than abstract. It is one of the clearest examples of a national identity rooted in open land.",
        "MO": "Macau is a Chinese special administrative region whose Portuguese colonial past remains unusually visible in street names, churches, and legal traditions. It is also one of the world's most intense gambling economies, with casino revenue that long outpaced far larger places. Few cities compress European colonial residue and Chinese hyper-capitalism so tightly.",
        "MQ": "Martinique is a French Caribbean island where rainforest mountains, Creole culture, rum distilleries, and market life give the island a character that is both elegant and deeply local. It is politically part of France, yet in music, speech, food, and everyday rhythm it belongs just as strongly to the Antilles. The result is a place where French institutions and Caribbean identity exist side by side in a way visitors notice immediately.",
        "MP": "The Northern Mariana Islands are a US commonwealth in the western Pacific, where tropical landscapes, Chamorro and Carolinian heritage, and warm reef water define the everyday feel of the islands. Saipan and nearby islands combine village life, marine scenery, and a layered Pacific identity that is easy to miss from a map alone. The territory's remoteness is part of what makes it feel so self-contained.",
        "MR": "Mauritania lies between North Africa and West Africa, and much of its identity comes from that frontier position across desert and Sahel. Caravan routes, Islamic scholarship, and nomadic traditions remain important reference points, giving the country a cultural texture shaped by movement, learning, and desert life. It is a country of huge distances, strong historical memory, and a landscape that feels both Saharan and Sahelian at once.",
        "MS": "Montserrat is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean whose capital, Plymouth, was buried after volcanic eruptions in the 1990s. That disaster reshaped the island's demography, economy, and geography in ways still visible today. It is one of the few places where a modern capital effectively became a ruin by natural force.",
        "MT": "Malta is a tiny Mediterranean archipelago whose strategic harbors made it important to Phoenicians, Romans, Arabs, crusading orders, the British Empire, and modern Europe. It also has some of the oldest free-standing stone temples in the world. The islands are small, but their location made them historically impossible to ignore.",
        "MU": "Mauritius is an Indian Ocean island state shaped by French and British colonial rule, plantation labor, and migration from India, Africa, China, and Europe. That history produced one of the world's most visibly plural island societies. The beaches are famous, but the deeper interest lies in how many worlds were brought together there.",
        "MV": "The Maldives is a chain of low coral atolls spread across the Indian Ocean, with average elevation so low that climate change is an immediate national concern. It became globally famous for overwater luxury tourism, but historically it was part of long Indian Ocean trade and Islamic networks. The country is beautiful in a way that also makes its vulnerability impossible to miss.",
        "MW": "Malawi wraps around Lake Malawi, one of Africa's great inland seas, and the lake shapes economy, ecology, and atmosphere across much of the country. It is sometimes called the 'Warm Heart of Africa,' a reputation tied to social friendliness as much as to branding. The country's strongest geographic feature is not a coast but freshwater on a vast scale.",
        "MX": "Mexico is one of the largest and most regionally diverse countries in the Americas, with Indigenous civilizations, Spanish colonialism, and modern nation-building all leaving strong marks. The state contains deserts, high plateaus, tropical coasts, Maya and Aztec legacies, and one of the world's most influential food cultures. It makes more sense as a set of powerful regional worlds than as a single stereotype.",
        "MY": "Malaysia is split between Peninsular Malaysia and part of Borneo, a geography that already tells you it is not a simple compact state. Malay, Chinese, Indian, Indigenous, and colonial influences shape its politics and everyday culture, especially through language and food. It is one of Southeast Asia's clearest examples of diversity managed through federal structure and pragmatic coexistence.",
        "MZ": "Mozambique has a long Indian Ocean coastline that tied it historically to the Swahili world, Portuguese empire, and wider trade across the ocean. Coastal cities, island heritage, dhow culture, seafood, marrabenta music, and marine life give the country an atmosphere that feels bright, rhythmic, and strongly maritime. Sea routes are essential to understanding why Mozambique feels so different from many inland southern African states.",
        "NA": "Namibia is one of the world's least densely populated countries, a fact that heightens the effect of its red dunes, desert coast, and huge night skies. It is one of Africa's great road-trip countries, with surreal scenery, desert-adapted wildlife, and a visual style that feels almost cinematic. People often come for the landscapes, but they stay impressed by how much quiet drama the country carries.",
        "NC": "New Caledonia is a French territory in the Pacific with one of the world's largest lagoons and a strong Indigenous Kanak political movement. Nickel mining, French settlement, and repeated debates over independence give the islands a political texture far more complex than a beach image would suggest. It is one of the clearest examples of unfinished decolonization in the Pacific.",
        "NE": "Niger occupies a huge stretch of the Sahara and Sahel, which means arid geography is central to nearly every part of life and movement. It has long been tied to caravan routes, Hausa and Tuareg worlds, desert cities, and a visual culture shaped by open space and bright light. Many people know the name only vaguely, but the country has a deep and distinctive Sahelian identity.",
        "NF": "Norfolk Island is a small Australian external territory whose social memory is strongly tied to descendants of the Bounty mutineers and their Tahitian companions. That lineage gives the island a cultural profile very different from mainland Australia. Cliffs, pine trees, and distance matter, but so does the strange historical route by which people ended up there.",
        "NG": "Nigeria is Africa's most populous country and one of its major cultural engines, with enormous influence in music, film, literature, religion, and business. It is also a federation of many large ethnic, linguistic, and religious communities, which is why the national story is never simple. Lagos alone would be historically interesting; the fact that it is only one piece of Nigeria tells you the scale involved.",
        "NI": "Nicaragua is the largest country in Central America, defined by lakes, volcanoes, colonial cities, and a surprisingly varied landscape between Pacific and Caribbean worlds. Granada and Leon give it some of the region's strongest colonial urban character, while islands, crater lakes, and surf towns add a more playful side. Its physical beauty is obvious, and the country often feels bigger and more varied than first-time visitors expect.",
        "NL": "The Netherlands is often introduced through canals, bicycles, and tulips, but its deeper history is about trade, water management, and republican urban power. Much of the country exists only because generations engineered land against the sea. That practical relationship with geography helps explain both Dutch urbanism and Dutch self-image.",
        "NO": "Norway stretches along one of the most deeply indented coastlines on earth, where fjords and mountains make travel feel shaped by geology at every turn. It became wealthy through shipping, oil, and a carefully managed welfare state, but older identities tied to fishing and seafaring remain strong. The country often feels spacious because it genuinely is built around landscape rather than density.",
        "NP": "Nepal rises from subtropical plains to the highest mountains on earth, including eight of the world's fourteen 8,000-meter peaks. It was never formally colonized, and its modern identity combines Hindu and Buddhist traditions with a long history of monarchy, then political transformation. For many people the Himalayas are the entry point, but the country is just as much about valley civilizations and pilgrimage.",
        "NR": "Nauru is one of the world's smallest republics, a single raised coral island in the Pacific whose modern history was transformed by phosphate mining. That extraction brought sudden wealth and then long-term ecological damage, leaving much of the island's interior scarred. Few states illustrate the costs of resource dependence so starkly at such a small scale.",
        "NU": "Niue is a self-governing island in free association with New Zealand, known less for sandy beach tourism than for limestone cliffs, caves, and clear Pacific water. It is one of the world's largest raised coral islands, which gives it a different physical feel from low atolls. Its tiny population and distance are not incidental; they shape the whole experience of the place.",
        "NZ": "New Zealand is an island country in the southwestern Pacific whose identity draws from both Maori Polynesian heritage and British settler colonialism. The two main islands contain glaciers, volcanoes, fjords, farmland, and cities, but the national story also turns on treaty politics and debates over biculturalism. It is often described as scenic first, though its constitutional and Indigenous questions are just as central.",
        "OM": "Oman occupies the southeastern corner of the Arabian Peninsula and has long looked outward through the Indian Ocean as much as inward toward the desert. Muscat's harbor setting, mountain villages, wadis, frankincense history, and the survival of the Ibadi branch of Islam all make the country stand apart in the Gulf. It feels quieter than some neighbors, but in a way that many travelers find more elegant than subdued.",
        "PA": "Panama is famous for the canal, and with good reason: few engineering works reshaped world trade as dramatically. Yet the country is also a narrow biological bridge between North and South America, with rainforests, Indigenous territories, and coastlines on two oceans. Passage is the obvious theme, but ecology and empire are close behind it.",
        "PE": "Peru contains one of the great historical cores of South America through the Inca world and the older civilizations that preceded it. Coast, Andes, and Amazon all meet inside one national territory, producing major regional contrasts in food, politics, and daily life. The country is globally famous for Machu Picchu, but the deeper story is a long chain of civilizations rather than a single site.",
        "PF": "French Polynesia is a vast French overseas collectivity spread across an enormous part of the South Pacific, where ocean distance matters more than most maps convey. Tahiti and Bora Bora are famous, but the territory includes many island groups with distinct histories and relationships to France. It is both a dreamscape in tourist imagination and a politically layered Pacific world.",
        "PH": "The Philippines is an archipelago of more than seven thousand islands whose history mixes Austronesian roots, Spanish colonization, American rule, and strong local regional identities. Christianity became deeply rooted here in a way unusual for Asia, while language and migration patterns kept the culture highly plural. It is a country where islands, diaspora, and colonial inheritance all remain central.",
        "PK": "Pakistan includes the Indus River system, Himalayan and Karakoram peaks, major urban centers, and cultures that span South and Central Asian influences. It is also a country of truck art, Sufi shrine culture, mountain hospitality, rich regional cuisines, and some of the most dramatic high-altitude scenery on earth. Too often discussed only through politics, it is in fact a very large and internally varied cultural world.",
        "PL": "Poland sits on the North European Plain and developed a national identity with unusually strong roots in language, music, Catholic tradition, and civic memory. Today it is a country of rebuilt old towns, hearty food, forests, castles, and cities whose cafe and cultural life feel increasingly confident and modern. The national character often comes across as both proud and deeply hospitable.",
        "PM": "Saint Pierre and Miquelon is a small French archipelago off Newfoundland, remarkable mainly because it is still politically France in the cold North Atlantic. Fishing, fog, and French civic life coexist there in a way that can feel delightfully improbable. It is less a tropical island territory than a tiny piece of Europe in subarctic waters.",
        "PN": "The Pitcairn Islands are one of the most isolated inhabited territories on earth and are inseparable from the story of the Bounty mutineers who settled there. Their population has long remained tiny, and access is difficult enough that remoteness becomes the main fact of life. Few inhabited places are so small and so mythologized at once.",
        "PG": "Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern half of New Guinea and is one of the most linguistically diverse countries on earth, with hundreds of languages spoken across mountains, forests, and island communities. Sing-sing traditions, carved art, bird-of-paradise imagery, coral coasts, and highland cultural worlds give it a richness that feels unlike anywhere else in the Pacific. It is one of those countries where human diversity itself is one of the defining landscapes.",
        "PR": "Puerto Rico is an unincorporated US territory in the Caribbean with a history shaped by Spanish colonialism, US rule after 1898, and ongoing debate over status. Its culture is distinctly Puerto Rican rather than merely American or generic Caribbean, especially in language, music, and migration. San Juan's fortifications tell one story; the island's unresolved constitutional position tells another.",
        "PT": "Portugal is one of Europe's oldest states within its current borders and one of the earliest great maritime empires of the modern era. Lisbon, Porto, the Atlantic coast, and the interior all reflect that long relationship with ocean trade, exploration, and migration. Its current size can make people forget how globally expansive Portuguese history once was.",
        "PS": "Palestine refers today mainly to the West Bank and Gaza, lands whose cities, villages, hills, and olive groves carry deep meaning in the history of the eastern Mediterranean. Palestinian identity is especially vivid through embroidery, olive oil, dabke, poetry, hospitality, family memory, and foods such as musakhan, maqluba, and knafeh. Bethlehem, Jerusalem, Hebron, Nablus, Ramallah, and Gaza each add their own texture, making Palestinian culture feel rooted, expressive, and unmistakably local.",
        "PW": "Palau is a small Pacific island country with extraordinary marine biodiversity and some of the world's most famous diving sites. It is also notable for environmental leadership, including strong marine protection policies that make conservation part of national identity. In Palau, the sea is not just scenery but a governing principle.",
        "PY": "Paraguay sits inland at the heart of South America, divided by the Paraguay River into the greener east and the sparsely populated Chaco in the west. It is one of the region's most bilingual countries, with Guarani widely spoken alongside Spanish in everyday life. That linguistic reality gives Paraguay a stronger Indigenous continuity than many outsiders expect.",
        "QA": "Qatar is a small Gulf peninsula whose global visibility is outsized because natural gas wealth funded rapid urban transformation, media networks, and diplomatic ambition. Doha's skyline is recent, but the older history involves pearling, tribal politics, and maritime trade. The country is physically small enough to cross quickly, yet it has developed a very visible identity through architecture, museums, and public investment on a grand scale.",
        "RE": "Reunion is a French island in the Indian Ocean where volcanic peaks, deep cirques, waterfalls, and black-sand coastlines create one of the most dramatic landscapes anywhere under French administration. Its culture blends African, Indian, European, Chinese, and Creole influences into a daily life shaped by mixed heritage, hiking culture, and intensely flavorful food. The island feels at once tropical, mountainous, and unusually cosmopolitan for its size.",
        "RO": "Romania stretches from the Carpathians to the Black Sea and preserves unusually visible traces of different European worlds in one country. Transylvania is only one part of the picture, alongside painted monasteries, village traditions, the Danube Delta, lively cities, and a strong folklore imagination. The country really rewards people who move beyond the Dracula shorthand.",
        "RS": "Serbia lies at a major Balkan crossroads where rivers, empires, Orthodoxy, and modern nationalism all left lasting marks. Belgrade feels intensely contemporary, with strong nightlife, cafe culture, and a confident urban personality, while monasteries, plains, and southern hill regions give the rest of the country a different tempo. Serbia is especially interesting because hospitality, music, and conversation are such a visible part of the national character.",
        "RU": "Russia spans eleven time zones and a huge sweep of Europe and Asia, a scale that makes it feel almost continental rather than national. Tsarist empire, Soviet power, literature, Orthodox tradition, Arctic frontiers, and contemporary authoritarianism all belong to the same story. The country is too large to summarize cleanly, which is itself one of its defining facts.",
        "RW": "Rwanda is a densely populated highland country in the African Great Lakes region, often called the 'land of a thousand hills' because the landscape really does roll endlessly in green layers. Kigali's order, mountain gorillas, coffee, tea, and a strong culture of craft and hospitality all shape the country's image today. Beauty, memory, and political discipline are tightly intertwined here, but the first impression is often how visually elegant the country feels.",
        "SA": "Saudi Arabia occupies most of the Arabian Peninsula and contains Islam's two holiest cities, Mecca and Medina, giving it unmatched religious significance for Muslims worldwide. Oil transformed the kingdom's global role, but older identities tied to caravan trade, tribal politics, and pilgrimage remain important. The country is now opening more visibly to tourism, but religion and state power still frame everything else.",
        "SB": "The Solomon Islands are a dispersed Melanesian archipelago where sea travel, village ties, and local island identity shape everyday life more than any single national center. Reef water, rainforest, carved traditions, and rich customary culture give the islands a strong sense of place that feels deeply Pacific and highly local at the same time. Visitors who make it there usually remember the lushness, the marine world, and the fact that each island group carries its own personality.",
        "SC": "Seychelles is an Indian Ocean republic of islands famous for granite boulders, beaches, and clear water, but it is equally notable for its Creole culture and environmental stewardship. The country has protected large marine and terrestrial areas, making conservation part of its national self-presentation. It feels polished on the surface, yet the island identity is rooted in a very specific and easygoing blend of histories.",
        "SD": "Sudan sits at the meeting of the Nile systems and has long been a crossroads linking North Africa, the Sahel, the Horn, and the Arab world. Ancient Nubian kingdoms, desert routes, river cultures, and strong traditions of poetry, hospitality, and music all shaped the country long before the modern state. Its historical importance is enormous even when the present is fractured.",
        "SE": "Sweden is a large Nordic state whose global image rests on welfare institutions, design, music, and a social ideal of balance, but it also has a deeper history as a Baltic power and industrial society. Most of the country is forested and sparsely populated compared with the urban south. The result is a national identity built from both modern administration and very old relationships with land and season.",
        "SO": "Somalia sits along one of Africa's longest coastlines, facing the Gulf of Aden and the Indian Ocean, and for centuries it was connected to trade routes reaching Arabia, India, and East Africa. Somali culture is especially known for oral poetry, camel traditions, seafaring, strong clan and family networks, and a language that carries an unusually rich poetic tradition. Even people who know little else about the country are often surprised by how deeply maritime, commercial, and literary its older identity is.",
        "SG": "Singapore is a sovereign city-state at the southern end of the Malay Peninsula, where one of the world's busiest ports sits alongside a highly managed urban experiment. Its population is ethnically mixed, its housing and transit systems are unusually centralized, and its state capacity is famous. The country fascinates people because it turned smallness into a governing strategy rather than a handicap.",
        "SH": "Saint Helena is a remote British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, best known to many people as the place of Napoleon's final exile. Its volcanic landscape and isolation made it historically useful as a prison island and stopping point on long sea routes. Even today, remoteness is not a detail there; it is the main condition of life.",
        "SI": "Slovenia sits where the Alps, the Balkans, the Mediterranean, and Central Europe meet, so its small territory contains remarkable geographic and cultural variety. It was the first republic to leave Yugoslavia and has often been seen as one of the region's quieter success stories. Caves, lakes, vineyards, and Habsburg-era urbanism all fit within a country small enough to cross quickly.",
        "SJ": "Svalbard is a Norwegian Arctic archipelago where glaciers, permafrost, polar bears, and extreme seasonal light make human settlement feel conditional rather than natural. Its legal status is also unusual because the Svalbard Treaty gave multiple countries economic rights there under Norwegian sovereignty. It is one of the few inhabited places that still feels fundamentally polar.",
        "SK": "Slovakia emerged as an independent state only in 1993, but the lands it covers carry older histories from the Kingdom of Hungary, the Habsburg monarchy, and Czechoslovakia. Mountain ranges, castles, and towns along the Danube give the country more geographic and architectural variety than many outsiders expect. It often gets overshadowed by neighbors, though its history is inseparable from theirs.",
        "SL": "Sierra Leone has one of West Africa's most striking peninsulas and one of its most historically charged names, linked to a colony founded for freed Black settlers. Freetown's setting, beach-lined coast, Krio culture, and musical energy give the country a vivid personality that many outsiders never hear about. Its historical arc is important, but so is the warmth and vitality of everyday life along the coast.",
        "SM": "San Marino claims to be one of the world's oldest republics, and its mountain-top fortifications above the Italian plain reinforce that sense of improbable survival. It is completely surrounded by Italy but remains fully sovereign, which is part of its enduring curiosity. Few microstates are so openly proud of their own age.",
        "SN": "Senegal sits on the Atlantic edge of West Africa and has long been one of the region's cultural and intellectual reference points. Dakar is influential in music, fashion, and political thought, while Goree Island and Saint-Louis tie the country to longer Atlantic and colonial histories. Senegal often serves as a reminder that cultural centrality does not always require geographic size.",
        "SR": "Suriname sits on South America's northern coast but often feels culturally closer to the Caribbean because of language, migration, and social rhythm. Dutch colonial rule and later immigration from South Asia and Java produced one of the most religiously and ethnically diverse populations in the region. Paramaribo's wooden architecture only hints at how unusual the national mix really is.",
        "SS": "South Sudan became independent in 2011, making it the world's newest widely recognized sovereign state. Its swamps, grasslands, cattle cultures, beadwork traditions, and immense wetlands give it a landscape and social world unlike anywhere else in East Africa. The political project remains unfinished, but the cultural and ecological distinctiveness of the country is already very clear.",
        "ST": "Sao Tome and Principe is a small island nation in the Gulf of Guinea with volcanic peaks, rainforest, and a colonial history built around sugar and later cacao. Because it lies well off the African mainland, it developed an insular Creole identity of its own. It remains one of the continent's least visited countries, which is part of its intrigue.",
        "SV": "El Salvador is the smallest mainland country in Central America, yet it packs volcanoes, Pacific surf, colorful towns, and dense regional flavor into a compact space. Pupusas, coffee landscapes, indigo history, and black-sand beaches give the country a more distinctive identity than its size suggests. It is easy to cross quickly, but not easy to summarize neatly.",
        "SX": "Sint Maarten is the Dutch side of the island shared with Saint Martin, and its economy is built heavily around tourism, ports, and services. The island's split administration is one of the Caribbean's most famous border oddities. Compared with quieter islands, Sint Maarten feels visibly urbanized and commercially tuned.",
        "SY": "Syria occupies one of the oldest continuously inhabited regions on earth, where ancient cities, desert routes, and Levantine culture created extraordinary historical depth. Damascene craft traditions, courtyard houses, jasmine-filled neighborhoods, soap making, music, and a famously generous food culture made the country one of the cultural centers of the Arab world. Aleppo, Damascus, Homs, coastal towns, and inland villages each belong to a landscape with a deeply rooted urban, agricultural, and artistic character.",
        "SZ": "Eswatini is a small southern African kingdom that retained monarchy as the central institution of state more visibly than most countries in the region. Hills, sugar lands, and wildlife reserves shape the landscape, but ceremonial and royal life shape the political image. The country is modest in size and distinctive in constitutional form.",
        "TC": "Turks and Caicos is a British Overseas Territory of low coral islands and cays, famous for clear shallow water and wide beaches. Historically it was more peripheral than major colonial hubs, which helped preserve a quieter and more dispersed physical character. The territory's strongest fact is still the sea itself.",
        "TD": "Chad stretches from the Sahara in the north through the Sahel toward more fertile southern zones, giving it one of the sharpest ecological gradients in Africa. That range creates major differences in livelihood, language, and landscape, from desert caravans to lake regions and greener south. Even people familiar with the name often underestimate how large and environmentally varied it is.",
        "TF": "The French Southern and Antarctic Lands are a scattering of remote French-administered territories in subantarctic and Antarctic waters, known more for wildlife colonies and scientific expeditions than for any settled civilian life. These islands and polar zones are places of albatrosses, penguins, seals, rough seas, and weather systems that feel almost planetary in scale. People do not go for ordinary sightseeing so much as for the rare experience of reaching one of the most isolated environments on earth.",
        "TG": "Togo is a narrow West African state running from the Gulf of Guinea northward into savanna, a shape that makes environmental change visible over relatively short distances. Markets, coast, hillside villages, textiles, and north-south contrast all play large roles in how the country is experienced. Its compactness makes the cultural and landscape shifts feel especially immediate.",
        "TH": "Thailand is one of Southeast Asia's major cultural anchors, known for never having been formally colonized and for building a modern state around monarchy, Buddhism, and strategic adaptation. Bangkok is one of the world's great urban intensities, while the rest of the country extends into rice plains, mountains, islands, and old capitals. Its accessibility to travelers can obscure how historically sophisticated the state really is.",
        "TJ": "Tajikistan is one of Central Asia's most mountainous countries, with the Pamirs giving it some of the highest and most remote inhabited terrain in the former Soviet world. Persian language heritage sets it apart from its largely Turkic-speaking neighbors. Much of the country's identity comes from altitude, isolation, and the persistence of valley-based regional life.",
        "TK": "Tokelau is a New Zealand territory made up of three low Pacific atolls with no airport and extremely limited outside access. Its remoteness and small population mean that ocean conditions directly shape transport, economy, and everyday rhythm. Few territories are so physically and logistically defined by the sea.",
        "TL": "Timor-Leste is one of Asia's youngest states and occupies the eastern half of Timor, where steep mountains drop toward reef-lined coasts and village life remains highly visible. Portuguese influence, Tetum language, Catholic traditions, woven textiles, and coffee-growing highlands all help give the country a distinct identity within island Southeast Asia. It still feels lightly visited and deeply local, which is part of its appeal for travelers who want somewhere genuinely different.",
        "TM": "Turkmenistan is a largely desert Central Asian state whose modern public image is dominated by authoritarian spectacle and monumental capital architecture. Beneath that lies an older history of caravan routes, oasis settlements, and tribal identities shaped by the Karakum Desert. It is one of the region's most unusual examples of state theater.",
        "TN": "Tunisia is a North African country where Carthaginian, Roman, Arab, Ottoman, French, and modern republican histories all remain visible. It is compact enough that Mediterranean coast, ancient ruins, medinas, and Sahara gateways can all fit into one trip. Tunisia often feels accessible, but its historical layers are very dense.",
        "TO": "Tonga is a Polynesian kingdom that retained indigenous monarchy rather than being fully absorbed into a settler colonial state. That continuity gives the country a political and ceremonial identity distinct within the Pacific. Coral islands, whale migration, and strong church life shape the setting, but monarchy remains one of the first facts to know.",
        "TR": "Turkey straddles Europe and Asia, but its real importance comes from inheriting the core lands of the Ottoman Empire and remaking them into a modern republic. Istanbul alone connects Byzantine, Ottoman, and contemporary urban history on a scale few cities can match. The country is regionally vast enough that Aegean coast, Anatolian plateau, Black Sea, and Kurdish southeast all feel like different historical conversations.",
        "TT": "Trinidad and Tobago is a two-island Caribbean state whose identity is far more urban, industrial, and multicultural than many outsiders expect. Trinidad shaped calypso, soca, and Carnival at a world level, while Tobago carries a smaller-island rhythm and tourism profile. The country is one of the region's strongest examples of how energy, migration, and culture can combine.",
        "TV": "Tuvalu is a tiny Pacific nation of low atolls where lagoon life, community ties, and ocean rhythm shape nearly everything. With so little elevation above sea level, the country is often discussed in climate terms, but daily life is also defined by fishing, church life, kinship, and the intimate scale of island communities. It is one of the clearest examples of how a very small place can still have a strong and distinct identity.",
        "TW": "Taiwan is a mountainous island off the coast of East Asia whose modern history includes Indigenous cultures, Qing rule, Japanese colonization, the arrival of the Republic of China government in 1949, and a vibrant contemporary democracy. Its political status remains contested internationally, which is part of why it is discussed so carefully. High-tech industry, night markets, temples, and strong local identity all coexist within a very compact island.",
        "TZ": "Tanzania brought together Tanganyika and Zanzibar into one state, a union that still matters to how the country is organized and imagined. It contains Serengeti plains, Kilimanjaro, Swahili coast history, and Indian Ocean island culture in a single national frame. Few African countries combine wildlife symbolism and coastal civilization so strongly.",
        "UA": "Ukraine is one of Europe's largest countries, with fertile plains, Black Sea coast, forest zones, and cities whose histories tie into several overlapping European worlds. It is especially rich in folk song, choral music, embroidery, Easter-egg artistry, wheat-field cuisine, and a literary culture that gives national identity a strong everyday presence. Kyiv, Lviv, Odesa, the Carpathians, and the steppe each show a different face of a country whose culture feels both regionally varied and strongly recognizable.",
        "UG": "Uganda sits where East African highlands meet the Great Lakes and the upper Nile, a geography that gives it unusual ecological richness. It is associated internationally with gorilla trekking, but kingdoms such as Buganda and later colonial and postcolonial politics are equally important to the national story. The country's greenery often surprises people expecting a simpler safari image.",
        "UM": "The United States Minor Outlying Islands are a scattered group of tiny US island territories and atolls spread mostly across the Pacific, with a few in the Caribbean. Most are uninhabited or have only temporary scientific or administrative presence, so they are defined more by reefs, seabirds, protected habitats, and remoteness than by settled community life. Their importance is geographic and ecological rather than cultural in the usual country-by-country sense.",
        "US": "The United States is continental in scale and federal in structure, which is why it often behaves less like one uniform country than like a collection of strong regional cultures sharing one political system. New England villages, Southern food traditions, Southwestern desert cities, Great Plains distances, Pacific coast innovation, and Hawaiian and Alaskan worlds all belong to the same map. Visitors often find that the country makes the most sense when you think of it as many local Americas at once rather than a single national mood.",
        "UY": "Uruguay is one of South America's smaller states, tucked between Brazil and Argentina, yet it developed a distinct civic identity around secularism, social reform, and relatively stable institutions. Its economy and culture are shaped by cattle, Atlantic coast, and the River Plate world rather than by dramatic mountain geography. The country often feels understated, which is part of what makes it distinctive in the region.",
        "UZ": "Uzbekistan is a central historical pillar of the Silk Road, with Samarkand, Bukhara, and Khiva standing among the most storied cities in Inner Asia. Soviet rule, cotton monoculture, and authoritarian post-independence governance all left major marks on the modern state. Tilework and old caravan routes may attract attention first, but the twentieth century is just as important to the country's story.",
        "VA": "Vatican City is the smallest independent state in the world and the institutional center of the Roman Catholic Church. Its area is tiny, yet it contains St. Peter's Basilica, the Sistine Chapel, and collections of art with global religious and cultural significance. It functions less like an ordinary country than like a concentrated seat of spiritual and diplomatic power.",
        "VC": "Saint Vincent and the Grenadines combines a volcanic main island with a string of smaller Grenadine islands spread across bright Caribbean water. The island of Saint Vincent also carries the important history of Garifuna resistance and forced deportation under British rule. It is a country where sailing scenery and anti-colonial memory unexpectedly share the same map.",
        "VE": "Venezuela stretches from Caribbean coast to Andean peaks, Llanos grasslands, and the table mountains of the Guiana Highlands, making it one of South America's most geographically varied states. Angel Falls, Caribbean beaches, joropo music, cacao, arepas, and the dramatic tepui landscape give the country one of the continent's most memorable physical personalities. It is a place of huge skies, strong regional accents, and landscapes so striking that many people are surprised more travelers do not talk about them first.",
        "VG": "The British Virgin Islands are a British Overseas Territory whose maze of channels, bays, and anchorages made them one of the Caribbean's classic sailing destinations. Their geography means that moving by boat is not a bonus experience but almost the natural way to understand the territory. They are small islands with a strongly nautical identity.",
        "VI": "The United States Virgin Islands are a Caribbean territory acquired by the United States from Denmark in 1917, a fact many people do not know until they look into the islands' history. Saint Thomas, Saint John, and Saint Croix each developed somewhat different characters, from cruise traffic to protected parks to plantation-era legacies. The territory is American in governance and unmistakably Caribbean in place.",
        "VN": "Vietnam stretches in a long S-shape along the South China Sea, creating major regional contrasts between north, center, and south. Rice terraces, imperial cities, coffee culture, night markets, street food, and a famously lively public street life give the country its everyday character. Hanoi, Hue, Hoi An, Da Nang, and Ho Chi Minh City each offer a different rhythm, but across them all you find strong regional pride, excellent food, and a social life that spills beautifully into the street.",
        "VU": "Vanuatu is a Melanesian island state known for active volcanoes, linguistic diversity, and village societies that remain highly visible in public life. It was once ruled jointly by Britain and France in the bizarre colonial arrangement known as the New Hebrides Condominium. Few countries combine geological drama and constitutional oddity so neatly.",
        "WF": "Wallis and Futuna is a French Pacific collectivity where Polynesian custom remains very strong despite the French administrative framework. The territory is remote enough that distance is part of its social reality, not just a map fact. It is one of those places where traditional chiefly structures and European state forms coexist in close proximity.",
        "WS": "Samoa is a Polynesian country where village life, chiefly titles, and the fa'a Samoa social system remain central to identity. It was also the first Pacific island country to regain independence in the twentieth century. The islands are lush and beautiful, but the stronger fact is how much cultural continuity remains intact.",
        "XD": "The UNDOF zone is not a normal sovereign country or civilian territory but a monitored buffer area on the Golan Heights. It is best understood as a map designation tied to observation, administration, and geography rather than to a resident national culture. The landscape itself is high, open, and dramatic, but the label refers to oversight and boundary management rather than to a destination in the usual sense.",
        "XK": "Kosovo is a landlocked Balkan republic whose cities, mountain landscapes, Ottoman-era heritage, and very young state institutions all shape the way it is experienced today. Pristina, Prizren, and smaller towns reveal a culture known for cafe life, hospitality, Albanian-majority identity, and a population that is strikingly youthful by European standards. It feels energetic and self-defining, with a sense of newness that is visible in both public life and national confidence.",
        "YE": "Yemen occupies the southwestern corner of Arabia and has one of the region's richest built and agricultural histories, from terrace farming to mud-brick tower cities such as Shibam and old Sana'a. Coffee, frankincense routes, mountain agriculture, stained-glass windows, qat gatherings, and some of the Arab world's most distinctive urban architecture all belong to its cultural identity. It is one of the great historic landscapes of Arabia, with a visual character so strong that even its skyline feels instantly recognizable.",
        "YT": "Mayotte is a French department in the Comoros archipelago, where lagoon waters, volcanic terrain, and Swahili-Islamic cultural roots meet French administrative structures in an unusual way. Daily life reflects Comorian heritage in language, family networks, and food, even though the island's political status ties it directly to France and the European Union. It is one of the Indian Ocean's clearest examples of how culture and sovereignty do not always map neatly onto each other.",
        "ZA": "South Africa contains some of the continent's most varied landscapes, from wine country and dramatic coasts to wildlife reserves and high plateaus. It has eleven official languages, world-famous food and wine scenes, strong design and music cultures, and cities with very different personalities from Cape Town to Johannesburg to Durban. The country's political history matters deeply, but so does the sheer range of cultural and geographic life packed into it.",
        "ZM": "Zambia is a landlocked southern African state of rivers, plateaus, and major wildlife areas, best known internationally for Victoria Falls on the Zambezi. Waterways, safari landscapes, copper-belt cities, and a generally open, friendly social tone give the country much of its character. It often feels spacious in both landscape and temperament.",
        "ZW": "Zimbabwe takes its name from Great Zimbabwe, the monumental stone city that stands as one of Africa's major archaeological sites and a key symbol of precolonial statecraft. The modern country combines highland cities, balancing-rock landscapes, wildlife reserves, Shona sculpture, and one of southern Africa's strongest traditions of stone carving and mbira music. It feels historically deep and visually distinctive, especially once you move beyond the single-image safari view many outsiders start with."
    ]

    static func description(for country: Country) -> String {
        let iso = country.iso2.uppercased()
        guard let description = customDescriptions[iso] else {
            assertionFailure("Missing overview description for \(iso) (\(country.name))")
            return fallbackDescription(for: country)
        }
        return firstSentences(in: description, maxCount: 3)
    }

    static func missingDescriptionCodes(in countries: [Country]) -> [String] {
        let countryCodes = Set(countries.map { $0.iso2.uppercased() })
        return countryCodes.subtracting(customDescriptions.keys).sorted()
    }

    private static func firstSentences(in text: String, maxCount: Int) -> String {
        let sentences = text
            .split(separator: ".")
            .map { $0.trimmingCharacters(in: .whitespacesAndNewlines) }
            .filter { !$0.isEmpty }

        guard !sentences.isEmpty else { return text }

        return sentences
            .prefix(maxCount)
            .map { "\($0)." }
            .joined(separator: " ")
    }

    private static func fallbackDescription(for country: Country) -> String {
        if let label = country.regionLabel, !label.isEmpty {
            return "\(country.name) is part of \(label). This entry is missing its full custom description in the current app dataset, but the country detail view is still available while the description list is being completed."
        }
        return "\(country.name) is included in the app's country dataset. This entry is missing its full custom description in the current app dataset, but the country detail view is still available while the description list is being completed."
    }
}
